    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-06-29T12:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-06-29T12:00:00-05:00" n="407"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d407">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 659.119/352</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Great Britain</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_LIB1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Laughlin</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-06-29T18:00:00+01:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">June 29, 1918, 6 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received 9.20 p.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>10964. War Trade Board from Doctor <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_TAE1"
                        >Taylor</persName>:</p>
                <p>No. 916. Have discussed Danish negotiations with Seydoux and <persName
                        corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_CLR1">Cecil</persName>. The blockade
                    authorities of the Allied countries are in agreement— <list>
                        <label>1.</label>
                        <item>That the status of Danish negotiations as outlined by me in accordance
                            with the situation on my departure offers no promise to the Associated
                            Governments;</item>
                        <label>2.</label>
                        <item>That so far as can be at present discerned, the policy of Associated
                            Governments is to sit tight;</item>
                        <label>3.</label>
                        <item>It is not the view of our allies that there is any danger of the
                            withdrawal of Danish ships from their present activities if the
                            negotiations should not eventuate into an agreement.</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <p>In reply to your No. 744, Department’s 8500, June 28, 8 p.m.,<note n="1"
                        xml:id="d407fn1">Not printed.</note> with reference to Oppenheimer’s
                    proposal, Dutch game unofficial and merely a feeler but obviously a blunder and
                    has been already buried.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_LIB1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Laughlin</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
